  "text": "The corrected correlation coefficient between climate and transfer was moderately strong at .37 (cumulative sample size ϭ 525) in [CITATION_1] . Additionally, transfer climate has functioned to moderate the influence of posttraining transfer interventions, as found by [CITATION_2] and [CITATION_3] , suggesting that climate should be considered before appending transfer intervention to training programs in hopes of increasing skill application. Specifically, [CITATION_4] found trainees who perceived a supportive transfer climate were more likely to use goals to support transfer of skills from a customer service skills training than those that perceived an unsupportive transfer climate. Transfer climate also was found to help explain the relationship between organizational learning 280 Human Resource Development Review / September 2007 culture and perceived innovation [CITATION_5] , indicating that climate influences other learning dimensions outside of training programs.",
